## Variogram Cloud and Experimental Variogram

The variogram cloud is a cloud of data points expressing their variability based on their interspacing. It provides the graphical representation of the values used to calculate the variogram.

## Variogram Fitting

library(geoR)
vario.ex<-variog(sic.100,option="bin")
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
vario.sphe<-(variofit(vario.ex,cov.model = "spher",
                      ini.cov.pars = c(15000,200)))
## variofit: covariance model used is spherical 
## variofit: weights used: npairs 
## variofit: minimisation function used: optim
par(mfrow=c(2,2),mar=c(3,3,1,1),mgp=c(2,1,0))
plot(vario.ex,main="Spherical")
lines.variomodel(cov.model="sphe",cov.pars=c(15000,100),nug=0,max.dist=350)
plot(vario.ex,main="Exponential")
lines.variomodel(cov.model="exp",cov.pars=c(15000,100),nug=0,max.dist=350)
plot(vario.ex,main="Exponential with Nugget Effect")
lines.variomodel(cov.model="exp",cov.pars=c(10000,100),nug=5000,max.dist=350)
plot(vario.ex,main="Exponential with Nugget Effect")
lines.variomodel(cov.model="matern",cov.pars=c(10000,100),nug=0,max.dist=350,kappa=0.5)

## Variogram fitting using 3 primary models (Spherical, Exponential and Gaussian)

library(geoR)

# Calculate empirical variogram
vario.ex <- variog(sic.100, option = "bin")
## variog: computing omnidirectional variogram
# Fit Spherical Variogram Model
vario.sphe <- variofit(vario.ex, cov.model = "spher", ini.cov.pars = c(15000, 200))
## variofit: covariance model used is spherical 
## variofit: weights used: npairs 
## variofit: minimisation function used: optim
# Fit Exponential Variogram Model
vario.exp <- variofit(vario.ex, cov.model = "exp", ini.cov.pars = c(15000, 100))
## variofit: covariance model used is exponential 
## variofit: weights used: npairs 
## variofit: minimisation function used: optim
# Fit Gaussian Variogram Model

vario.gau <- variofit(vario.ex, cov.model = "gau", nug = 0)
## variofit: covariance model used is gaussian 
## variofit: weights used: npairs 
## variofit: minimisation function used: optim
## Warning in variofit(vario.ex, cov.model = "gau", nug = 0): initial values not
## provided - running the default search
## variofit: searching for best initial value ... selected values:
##               sigmasq   phi     tausq     kappa
## initial.value "9490.33" "45.08" "4745.16" "0.5"
## status        "est"     "est"   "est"     "fix"
## loss value: 25425305330.8636
# Set up the plotting layout
par(mfrow = c(2, 2), mar = c(3, 3, 1, 1), mgp = c(2, 1, 0))

# Plot empirical variogram with the Spherical model
plot(vario.ex, main = "Spherical")
lines.variomodel(cov.model = "sphe", cov.pars = c(15000, 100), nug = 0, max.dist = 350)

# Plot empirical variogram with the Exponential model
plot(vario.ex, main = "Exponential")
lines.variomodel(cov.model = "exp", cov.pars = c(15000, 100), nug = 0, max.dist = 350)

# Plot empirical variogram with the Gaussian model
plot(vario.ex, main = "Gaussian")
lines.variomodel(cov.model = "gau", cov.pars = c(15000, 100, 0.1), nug = 0, max.dist = 350)

Performing Ordinry kriging based on the generated variogram models

library(geoR)

# Define the prediction grid
pred.grid <- expand.grid(seq(0, 350, l = 51), seq(0, 220, l = 51))

# Perform kriging with Spherical Variogram Model
kc_sphe <- krige.conv(sic.100, loc = pred.grid, krige = krige.control(cov.model = "spherical", cov.pars = c(15000, 100)))
## krige.conv: model with constant mean
## krige.conv: Kriging performed using global neighbourhood
# Perform kriging with Exponential Variogram Model
kc_exp <- krige.conv(sic.100, loc = pred.grid, krige = krige.control(cov.model = "exp", cov.pars = c(15000, 100)))
## krige.conv: model with constant mean
## krige.conv: Kriging performed using global neighbourhood
# Perform kriging with Gaussian Variogram Model
kc_gau <- krige.conv(sic.100, loc = pred.grid, krige = krige.control(cov.model = "gau", cov.pars = c(15000, 100, 0.1),nug = 0.01))
## krige.conv: model with constant mean
## krige.conv: Kriging performed using global neighbourhood
# Set up the plotting layout
par(mfrow = c(2, 2), mar = c(3, 3, 1, 1), mgp = c(2, 1, 0))

# Defining a color palette
rgb.palette <- colorRampPalette(c("blue", "lightblue", "orange", "red"), space = "rgb")

# Plot kriged estimates with the Spherical model
image(kc_sphe, loc = pred.grid, col = rgb.palette(20), xlab = "Coord X", ylab = "Coord Y", borders = sic.borders, main = "Spherical Kriging Estimates")

# Plot kriged variances with the Spherical model
image(kc_sphe, kc_sphe$krige.var, loc = pred.grid, col = rgb.palette(20), xlab = "Coord X", ylab = "Coord Y", borders = sic.borders, main = "Spherical Kriging Variances")

# Plot kriged estimates with the Exponential model
image(kc_exp, loc = pred.grid, col = rgb.palette(20), xlab = "Coord X", ylab = "Coord Y", borders = sic.borders, main = "Exponential Kriging Estimates")

# Plot kriged variances with the Exponential model
image(kc_exp, kc_exp$krige.var, loc = pred.grid, col = rgb.palette(20), xlab = "Coord X", ylab = "Coord Y", borders = sic.borders, main = "Exponential Kriging Variances")

# Plot kriged estimates with the Gaussian model
image(kc_gau, loc = pred.grid, col = rgb.palette(20), xlab = "Coord X", ylab = "Coord Y", borders = sic.borders, main = "Gaussian Kriging Estimates")

# Plot kriged variances with the Gaussian model
image(kc_gau, kc_gau$krige.var, loc = pred.grid, col = rgb.palette(20), xlab = "Coord X", ylab = "Coord Y", borders = sic.borders, main = "Gaussian Kriging Variances")

Evaluating the accuracy of the kriging results

library(geoR)

# Assuming sic.100$data is a named numeric vector
observed_values <- sic.100$data[order(names(sic.100$data))]

# Perform kriging with Spherical Variogram Model
kc_sph <- krige.conv(sic.100, loc = pred.grid, krige = krige.control(cov.model = "spherical", cov.pars = c(15000, 100)))
## krige.conv: model with constant mean
## krige.conv: Kriging performed using global neighbourhood
# Assuming sic.100$data is a named numeric vector
observed_values <- sic.100$data[order(names(sic.100$data))]

# Check the structure of sic.100$data
str(sic.100$data)
##  Named num [1:100] 151 255 79 191 194 334 107 296 394 394 ...
##  - attr(*, "names")= chr [1:100] "13" "14" "22" "23" ...
# Check the lengths
length(observed_values)
## [1] 100
length(kc_sph$predict)
## [1] 2601
# Ensure kc_sph$predict is ordered based on names
kc_sph$predict_ordered <- kc_sph$predict[order(names(sic.100$data))]

# Create a data frame with observed values and corresponding kriged values
comparison_data <- data.frame(
  Observed = observed_values,
  Kriged = kc_sph$predict_ordered
)

# Check the length again
length(comparison_data$Observed)
## [1] 100
length(comparison_data$Kriged)
## [1] 100
# Plot the scatter plot
plot(comparison_data$Observed, comparison_data$Kriged,
     xlab = "Observed", ylab = "Kriged", main = "Spherical Kriging")

# Add a 1:1 line for reference
abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "red")

# Plot observed vs. kriged estimates for Spherical model

Kriging with transformed data

library(geoR)

# Define the prediction grid
pred.grid_tr <- expand.grid(seq(0, 350, l = 51), seq(0, 220, l = 51))

# 1. Data Transformation (Example: Log Transformation)
transformed_data_kc <- log(sic.100$data)

# 2. Create a new geodata object for transformed data
geodata_transformed_kc <- list(coords = sic.100$coords[, c("V2", "V3")], data = transformed_data_kc)

# Perform Kriging on Transformed Data
kc_sph_tr <- krige.conv(geodata_transformed_kc, loc = pred.grid_tr, krige = krige.control(cov.model = "spherical", cov.pars = c(15000, 100)))
## krige.conv: model with constant mean
## krige.conv: Kriging performed using global neighbourhood
# Perform kriging with Exponential Variogram Model
kc_exp_tr <- krige.conv(geodata_transformed_kc, loc = pred.grid_tr, krige = krige.control(cov.model = "exponential", cov.pars = c(15000, 100)))
## krige.conv: model with constant mean
## krige.conv: Kriging performed using global neighbourhood
# Perform kriging with Gaussian Variogram Model
kc_gau_tr <- krige.conv(geodata_transformed_kc, loc = pred.grid_tr, krige = krige.control(cov.model = "gaussian", cov.pars = c(15000, 100, 0.1),nug = 0.01))
## krige.conv: model with constant mean
## krige.conv: Kriging performed using global neighbourhood
# Set up the plotting layout
par(mfrow = c(2, 2), mar = c(3, 3, 1, 1), mgp = c(2, 1, 0))

# Defining a color palette
rgb.palette <- colorRampPalette(c("blue", "lightblue", "orange", "red"), space = "rgb")

# Plot kriged estimates with the Spherical model
image(kc_sph_tr, loc = pred.grid_tr, col = rgb.palette(20), xlab = "Coord X", ylab = "Coord Y", borders = sic.borders, main = "Spherical Kriging Estimates-Transformed Data")

# Plot kriged variances with the Spherical model
image(kc_sph_tr, kc_sph_tr$krige.var, loc = pred.grid_tr, col = rgb.palette(20), xlab = "Coord X", ylab = "Coord Y", borders = sic.borders, main = "Spherical Kriging Variances-Transformed Data")

# Plot kriged estimates with the Exponential model
image(kc_exp_tr, loc = pred.grid_tr, col = rgb.palette(20), xlab = "Coord X", ylab = "Coord Y", borders = sic.borders, main = "Exponential Kriging Estimates-Transformed Data")

# Plot kriged variances with the Exponential model
image(kc_exp_tr, kc_exp_tr$krige.var, loc = pred.grid, col = rgb.palette(20), xlab = "Coord X", ylab = "Coord Y", borders = sic.borders, main = "Exponential Kriging Variances-Transformed")

# Plot kriged estimates with the Gaussian model
image(kc_gau_tr, loc = pred.grid_tr, col = rgb.palette(20), xlab = "Coord X", ylab = "Coord Y", borders = sic.borders, main = "Gaussian Kriging Estimates-Transformed Data")

# Plot kriged variances with the Gaussian model
image(kc_gau_tr, kc_gau_tr$krige.var, loc = pred.grid, col = rgb.palette(20), xlab = "Coord X", ylab = "Coord Y", borders = sic.borders, main = "Gaussian Kriging Variances-Transformed Data")

Kriging validation with transformed data

library(geoR)

str(sic.100$coords)
##  num [1:100, 1:2] 29.5 33.8 46.8 48.7 49.3 ...
##  - attr(*, "dimnames")=List of 2
##   ..$ : chr [1:100] "13" "14" "22" "23" ...
##   ..$ : chr [1:2] "V2" "V3"
dim(sic.100$coords)
## [1] 100   2
# Assuming sic.100$data is your raw data

#Spherical model
# 1. Data Transformation (Example: Log Transformation)
transformed_data <- log(sic.100$data)

# 2. Create a new geodata object for transformed data
geodata_transformed <- list(coords = sic.100$coords[, c("V2", "V3")], data = transformed_data)

# 3. Perform Kriging on Transformed Data
kc_sph_transformed <- krige.conv(geodata_transformed, loc = pred.grid, krige = krige.control(cov.model = "spherical", cov.pars = c(15000, 100)))
## krige.conv: model with constant mean
## krige.conv: Kriging performed using global neighbourhood
# 3. Evaluate Accuracy
# 4. Extract kriged values in order
kc_sph_transformed$predict_ordered <- kc_sph_transformed$predict[order(names(transformed_data))]

# 5. Create a data frame with observed values and corresponding kriged values
comparison_data_transformed <- data.frame(
  Observed = transformed_data[order(names(transformed_data))],
  Kriged = kc_sph_transformed$predict_ordered
)


# Plot observed vs. kriged values for both raw and transformed data
plot(comparison_data$Observed, comparison_data$Kriged,
     xlab = "Observed", ylab = "Kriged", main = "Spherical Kriging (Raw Data)")
abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "red")

plot(comparison_data_transformed$Observed, comparison_data_transformed$Kriged,
     xlab = "Observed", ylab = "Kriged", main = "Spherical Kriging (Transformed Data)")
abline(a = 0, b = 1, col = "red")

Calculating the RMSE

# Spherical Model Kriging
squared_errors_sph <- (comparison_data_transformed$Observed - comparison_data_transformed$Kriged)^2

# Calculate the mean squared error
mse_sph <- mean(squared_errors_sph)

# Calculate the root mean squared error
rmse_sph <- sqrt(mse_sph)

# Print or use the RMSE value
print(rmse_sph)
## [1] 1.076981
# RMSE - Exponential Model Kriging
squared_errors_exp <- (comparison_data_transformed_exp$Observed - comparison_data_transformed_exp$Kriged)^2

# Calculate the mean squared error
mse_exp <- mean(squared_errors_exp)

# Calculate the root mean squared error
rmse_exp <- sqrt(mse_exp)

# Print or use the RMSE value
print(rmse_exp)
## [1] 1.109022
# RMSE - Gaussian Model Kriging
squared_errors_gau <- (comparison_data_transformed_gau$Observed - comparison_data_transformed_gau$Kriged)^2

# Calculate the mean squared error
mse_gau <- mean(squared_errors_gau)

# Calculate the root mean squared error
rmse_gau <- sqrt(mse_gau)

# Print or use the RMSE value
print(rmse_gau)
## [1] 26.03282
